Adjust Filenames
================

   Let's go back to the previous example.  Again, supporsed that you
have already copied a CD-ROM book to `/dict' on a hard disk, but it is
not compressed.  The book has the following files under `/dict'.
However, unlike the previous example, file and directory names under
`/dict' consist of upper case letters, and filenames have the version
number `;1' in their tails.

     /dict/CATALOG;1
     /dict/LANGUAGE;1
     /dict/GERMAN/START;1
     /dict/FRENCH/START;1
     /dict/ITALIAN/START;1

   After the compression by `ebzip', they will be as the following:

     /dict/CATALOG;1
     /dict/LANGUAGE.EBZ;1
     /dict/GERMAN/START.EBZ;1
     /dict/FRENCH/START.EBZ;1
     /dict/ITALIAN/START.EBZ;1

`ebzip' keeps "case" (upper or lower) and "suffix" of filenames as
original form.  The following table displayes how a filename of `start'
file changes.

case/suffix                   before compression     after compresssion     
lower/none                    start                  start.ebz              
lower/dot                     start.                 start.ebz              
lower/version                 start;1                start.ebz;1            
lower/dot+version             start.;1               start.ebz;1            
upper/none                    START                  START.EBZ              
upper/dot                     START.                 START.EBZ              
upper/version                 START;1                START.EBZ;1            
upper/dot+version             START.;1               START.EBZ;1            

   The `--case' and `--suffix' options allows you to modify these case
and suffix styles of output filenames.  The `--case' option takes an
argument, and it must be `upper' or `lower'.  The option sets the case
of output filenames to upper or lower.  Also the `--suffix' option
takes an argument, and it must be `none', `dot', `version' or `both'.
The option sets the suffix style of output filenames to none, dot,
version or both (dot+version).


